From: wuxing <web8stars@gmail.com>
Subject: [PATCH] fix: handle non-string and media payloads in deliver callback

The `deliver` callback in `dispatchInbound` assumed payload was either
a string or an object with `.text`/`.body` fields. However, the OpenClaw
gateway may pass:

1. Objects with `.content` field instead of `.text` (e.g. `{content: "..."}`)
2. Media-only payloads with no text at all (e.g. TTS voice responses:
   `{mediaUrl: "/tmp/.../voice.mp3", audioAsVoice: true}`)

In both cases, `String(payload)` produced `"[object Object]"` which was
sent to HXA Hub and displayed in chat.

Fix: robustly extract text from multiple possible fields, handle nested
objects, and fall back to `[media] <url>` for media-only payloads.

---
 index.ts | 20 ++++++++++++++++----
 1 file changed, 16 insertions(+), 4 deletions(-)

diff --git a/index.ts b/index.ts
index d9e8962..3b33e1e 100644
--- a/index.ts
+++ b/index.ts
@@ -1109,10 +1109,24 @@ async function dispatchInbound(params: InboundParams) {
     cfg,
     dispatcherOptions: {
       deliver: async (payload: any) => {
-        const text =
-          typeof payload === "string"
-            ? payload
-            : payload?.text ?? payload?.body ?? String(payload);
+        let text: string;
+        if (typeof payload === "string") {
+          text = payload;
+        } else if (typeof payload === "object" && payload !== null) {
+          // Extract text from various payload formats
+          text = payload.text ?? payload.content ?? payload.body ?? payload.message ?? "";
+          if (typeof text !== "string") {
+            text = text?.text ?? text?.content ?? "";
+          }
+          if (typeof text !== "string") text = "";
+          // Handle media payloads (TTS voice, images, etc.)
+          const mediaUrl = payload.mediaUrl || (payload.mediaUrls && payload.mediaUrls[0]) || "";
+          if (mediaUrl && !text) {
+            text = "[media] " + mediaUrl;
+          }
+        } else {
+          text = String(payload ?? "");
+        }
         if (!text?.trim()) return;

         try {
